AN ACT relating to crimes; increasing the penalties for sex
trafficking a child or facilitating the sex trafficking of a
child; and providing other matters properly relating
thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law makes the offense of sex trafficking a child a category A felony,
2 punishable by imprisonment in the state prison for life with the possibility of
3 parole. The minimum number of years that must be served before becoming
4 eligible for parole and the amount of a fine imposed for such an offense are based
5 upon the age of the child when the offense is committed. For an offense committed
6 against a child who is less than 14 years of age when the offense is committed: (1)
7 eligibility for parole begins when a minimum of 15 years has been served; and (2)
8 the person may be punished by a fine of not more than $20,000. For an offense
9 committed against a child who is at least 14 years of age but less than 16 years of
10 age when the offense is committed: (1) eligibility for parole begins when a
11 minimum of 10 years has been served; and (2) the person may be punished by a
12 fine of not more than $10,000. For an offense committed against a child who is at
13 least 16 years of age but less than 18 years of age when the offense is committed:
14 (1) eligibility for parole begins when a minimum of 5 years has been served; and
15 (2) the person may be punished by a fine of not more than $10,000. (NRS 201.300)
16 Section 1 of this bill increases the penalties for the offense of sex trafficking a
17 child and provides that for an offense committed against a child who is: (1) less
18 than 14 years of age when the offense is committed, the perpetrator must be
19 punished by imprisonment in the state prison for life either without the possibility
20 of parole or with the possibility of parole beginning when a minimum of 20 years
21 has been served, and by a fine of not more than $40,000; (2) at least 14 years of age
22 but less than 16 years of age when the offense is committed, the perpetrator must be
23 punished by imprisonment in the state prison for life with the possibility of parole
24 beginning when a minimum of 15 years has been served, and by a fine of not more
25 than $20,000; and (3) at least 16 years of age but less than 18 years of age when the
26 offense is committed, the perpetrator must be punished by imprisonment in the state
